House Speaker Kevin McCarthy Drops Hammer On Democrats

He went there.

House Speaker Kevin McCarthy has delivered on a previous pledge to bar two members of California’s Democratic congressional delegation from serving on the Select Committee on Intelligence.

The California Republican has blocked Reps. Adam Schiff and Eric Swalwell from the panel, fulfilling a promise he made before the midterm elections to remove them should the GOP win back the House majority and make him speaker.

“House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries (D-N.Y.) had written to McCarthy on Saturday asking that both Schiff and Swalwell be seated on the Intel panel, where membership assignments come solely at the discretion of the Speaker,” The Hill reported.

However, McCarthy countered that previous actions by both lawmakers have made them unqualified to serve on such a sensitive committee.

“In order to maintain a standard worthy of this committee’s responsibilities, I am hereby rejecting the appointments of Representative Adam Schiff and Representative Eric Swalwell to serve on the Intelligence Committee,” McCarthy responded to Jeffries on Tuesday.

Last Wednesday, the main Armenian event of the year was held in Paris - a gala dinner of Coordinating Council of Armenian Organizations in France (CCAF)

For the second year in a row, French president Emmanuel Macron was absent. He was represented by the Interior Minister Gérald Darmanin, third in the protocol order, who delivered an unprecedented strong message of support, asserting that Armenia's opponents are as well France's opponents. He also joked that the kinship and close ties between France and Armenia are so strong that one feels at home at a CCAF dinner, and, in fact, the minister of the interior is the most appropriate person to speak.

Gabriel Attal, the delegate of the Minister of Economy in charge of public accounts, was also present at this dinner, sitting next to him, so was Claire Edon, the French defender of rights.

Xavier Bertrand, president of the Hauts-de-France region, Georges Siffredi, president of the Hauts-de-Seine region, Bruno Retailleau, president of the LR senators (senate majority), Eric Ciotti, LR deputy and head, and Olivier Faure, first secretary of the PS (Socialist Party), sat at the head table.

Euro-MPs Nathalie Loiseau and François-Xavier Bellamy as well as deputies Jérôme Guedj, Guillaume Kasbarian, Mohamed Laqhila, Constance Le Grip, Sylvain Maillard, Astrid Panosyan Bouvet, Anne-Laurence Petel (France-Armenia committee president), Isabelle Santiago, Sarah Tanzili, Sabrina Agresti-Roubache, Aurore Bergé, Jean-Louis Bourlanges, Sébastien Delogu and senators Patrick Kanner, Christian Cambon, Marie-Arlette Carlotti, Pierre Ouzoulias, Stéphane Ravier, David Assouline, Valérie Boyer, Brigitte Devesa, Gilbert-Luc Devinaz, among others, also attended the dinner. 

Many mayors and their delegates as well as representatives of friendly communities such as Cypriot Community of France, the CCACF, the CDK-F (kurdish community) and the CRIF (jewish lobby) were present too. 

From the beginning of the dinner, Charles Villeneuve, the master of ceremonies, set the tone recalling the "special gravity" of the events that are unfolding in Artsakh and Armenia. "We cannot witness a slow and inexorable death in general indifference and be so prompt to help Ukraine", he denounced. 

Paris Mayor Anne Hidalgo gave a detailed insight of the appalling situation going on in Artsakh. "The blockade is an act of war. A cowardly war, a sneaky war, but a war. A war that takes place right under our eyes and in a deafening silence." She blamed the international community, the Minsk group and namely France, for their indifference toward the situation in Artsakh, "which makes it even more so unbearable" and "results in a lack of action". She recalled her initiative to promote a health program dedicated to the victims of the 44-day war in Armenia and Artsakh, confident that "for the first time, a French city will support the Armenians of Artsakh with direct help, as soon as the corridor reopens". In this regard, she called on France to demand, on behalf of the Minsk Group, the immediate opening of the corridor to humanitarian help.

"France cannot remain indifferent or silent toward what is happening in this part of Armenia so far away and yet so close to us." She also held Russia responsible for leaving carte blanche to Baku-Ankara axis to achieve territorial continuity between the Caspian and Turkey. She announced a major conference planned in Paris at City Hall during this spring in order to support the Armenians of Armenia and Artsakh so as to keep alerting about what is going on on site. She also renewed her wish to see the Misak Manouchian group enter the Pantheon. "By giving their lives, they fought for the values of France and for it to remain a country of generosity and solidarity. We also owe them our support for Armenia and Artsakh.”
